/*
** Gratian: changes to text, coding, etc.
** 
** Electronic notes: coding ASCII, 40 hex used for "Paragraph sign", 
** (normally) no trailing blanks at end of line.
** 
** The text is as it appears in the edition of Emil Friedberg 
** (Leipzig 1879) except that
** 
** a)   hyphens have been removed.
** b)   obvious printing errors have been corrected, but not if 
**      there is a possibility that these could represent medieval 
**      ms. readings (for details of emendations see the 
**      introduction to G. Silagi and T. Reuter, Wortkonkordanz zum 
**      Decretum Gratiani, Munich 1989/90)
** c)   some abbreviations have been expanded.
** d)   Friedberg's use of quotation marks has been rationalised 
**      (single quotes [27 hex] for quotes within quotes) and 
**      completed as far as possible, as has his somewhat erratic 
**      use of square brackets to distinguish additions made by the 
**      Correctores Romani to the text. No attempt has been made to 
**      distinguish between opening and closing quotes.
** 
** Some of the text has been enclosed between a minus and a plus sign to 
** denote commentary:
** 
** a)   page numbers
** b)   chapter, book, etc. divisions
** c)   square-bracketed additions by the CR (see d above)
** d)   the word PALEA
** e)   the thirteenth century paragraph divisions (@. 1, etc.)
** f)   titles
** 
** The text is otherwise coded only by the insertion of OCP-style 
** markers, enclosed in pointed brackets as usual. The references 
** used are:
** 
** L)   for line (the program used for intermediate work was OCP)
** S)   for page (the original project was carried out in German)
** T)   for text type, i.e.
**     A denotes dictum ante
**     P denotes dictum post
**     Q denotes quaestionatio
**     I denotes inscriptio
**     R denotes rubric
**     T denotes text, i.e. the piece of canon law being quoted
** P)   for palea: 1 for yes, 0 for no
** 1)   for the major division
** 2)   the number of the major division
** 3)   in the case of the Causae, the number of the Quaestio
** 4)   the number of the chapter
** 
** Any further queries may be addressed to T. Reuter at the MGH, e-
** mail A400101@DM0LRZ01.EARN
*/

